mizing And Popularizing Dance In Canada During The 1950S / rLindgren, Allana C. -- t9. Gender, Spirits, And Beer: Representing Female And Male Bodies In Canadian Alcohol Ads, 1930S-1970S / rKrasnick Warsh, Cheryl / Marquis, Greg -- tBodies In Contests -- t10. Nudity As Embodied Citizenship And Spectacle: Pageants At Canada'S Nudist Clubs, 1949-1975 / rShantz, Mary-Ann -- t11. Modelling The U.N.'S Mission In Semi-Formal Wear: Edmonton'S Miss United Nations Pageants Of The 1960S / rBrookfield, Tarah -- tPart Three: Regulating Bodies -- tTransformations, Medicalization, And The Healthy Body -- t12. Obesity In Children: A Medical Perception, 1920-1980 / rMitchinson, Wendy -- t13. Public Body, Private Health: Mediscope, The Transparent Woman, And Medical Authority, 1959 / rMinnett, Valerie -- t14. Trans/Forming The Citizen Body In Wartime: National And Local Public Discourse On Women'S Bodies And "Body Work" For Women During The Second World War / rSmith, Helen / Wakewich, Pamela -- tRe/Producing Productive Bodies -- t15. "Flesh, Bone, And Blood": Working-Class Bodies And The Canadian Communist Press, 1922-1956 / rToews, Anne Frances -- t16. "Better Teachers, Biologically Speaking": The Authority Of The "Marrying-Kind" Of Teacher In Schools, 1945-1960 / rLlewellyn, Kristina R. -- t17. Contesting A Canadian Icon: Female Police Bodies And The Challenge To The Masculine Foundations Of The Royal Canadian Mounted Police In The 1970S / rReilly Schmidt, Bonnie -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom fur coats to nude paintings, and from sports to beauty contests, the body has been central to the literal and figurative fashioning of ourselves as individuals and as a nation. In this first collection on the history of the body in Canada, an interdisciplinary group of scholars explores the multiple ways the body has served as a site of contestation in Canadian history in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.Showcasing a variety of methodological approaches, Contesting Bodies and Nation in Canadian History includes essays on many themes that engage with the larger historical relationship between the body and nation: medicine and health, fashion and consumer culture, citizenship and work, and more. The contributors reflect on the intersections of bodies with the concept of nationhood, as well as how understandings of the body are historically contingent. The volume is capped off with a critical introductory chapter by the editors on the history of bodies and the development of the body as a category of analysis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2019) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aNicholas, Jane, eauthor.40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442663152423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442663152.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG